              ]
            }
          ],
          "SAMPLE": [
            {
              "pointer": "",
              "coded_information": null,
              "free_text": [
                "Metal discs of natural Zr, Ta, Re as sample-filter.",
                "Radiator-samples - metal plates :",
                "Zr - 0.00435 at/b, Ta - 0.00116 at/b, Re - 0.00976at/b,",
                "U-238 - o.000437 at/b and 0.00121 at/b."
              ]
            }
          ],
          "ANALYSIS": [
            {
              "pointer": "",
              "coded_information": null,
              "free_text": [
                "Total transmission and partial capture cross-sections",
                "were determined from measured TOF spectra of various",
                "coincidence multiplicities of gamma-quanta after",
                "background subtraction.",
                "Doppler coefficients were determined by measurement",
                "of Ta (0.0138 at/b) total transmission at nitrogen",
                "temperature."
              ]
            }
          ],
          "CORRECTION": [
            {
              "pointer": "",
              "coded_information": null,
              "free_text": [
                "For resonance-self-shielding using ENDF/B-6.7 data."
              ]
            }
          ],
          "COMMENT": [
            {
              "pointer": "",
              "coded_information": null,
              "free_text": [
                "Of authors. Exp. group total c-s for Ta and Re differ",
                "10-70 % in most of energy groups from calculated",
                "  (by ENDF/B-6.7, BROND) values.",
                "Exp. and calculated capture c-s for Re coincide,",
                "for Zr and Ta - different within the limits of exp.",
                "errors.",
                "Of compiler.",
                "!!!!   Figures of S,ISINN-12,59,2004 are not good",
                " for digitizing, are given in LIN-LIN scale,          4",
                "of little size. So quality of digitized data is low."
              ]
            }
